The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 LG embraces Oracle solution

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 (From left) Arindam Bose, head of IT systems at LG Electronics India, Mark Gibbs, senior vice-president (application) at Oracle Corporation, Asia Pacific division, and Krishan Dhawan, managing director of Oracle India, in New Delhi on Monday. Picture by Prem Singh

 New Delhi, May 2: LG Electronics India Ltd will invest $5 million for enterprise resource planning and marketing activities using Oracle?s e-business suite.

 The project will cover finance, manufacturing, sales, purchasing, inventory management and service domain. The Korean electronic major will also use the e-business suite for its other activities that are related to online sales and promotion. 

 Arindam Bose, head of IT systems at LG Electronics India (LGEIL), said, ?With the growth of our Indian operations, we felt an increasing need to enhance the response time of our ERP as well as improve the scalability, security and flexibility of the existing IT systems. We have decided to replace the custom developed ERP with the standards-based and fully integrated Oracle applications.? The implementation of Oracle applications is expected to be completed by July. This will help LGEIL seamlesly integrate with its parent company and other LG businesses worldwide. 

 Krishan Dhawan, managing director of Oracle India, said, ?Information is emerging as a differentiator for businesses in areas of financial, purchasing, manufacturing, sales and inventory management. The Oracle information architecture includes the Oracle e-business suite, along with the underlying data base and application server technologies. This integrated architecture effectively provides business managers with high quality, real-time information from a single source of truth.? 

 The system is aimed at making the business process faster, effective and productive, which will enable LGEIL become more competitive. 




